<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n01018g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n01" href="#n01018g">N01 (VI.B.10)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n01all.htm#n01018g"> 18(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> arquebusier</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">How Cellini cured himself of this indisposition and &ldquo;got his man&rdquo; (as we are now saying) is thus told and I wonder if there is anything more dramatically effective in the pages of Dumas. &ldquo;Better to me than courting a sweetheart,&rdquo; he says with savage joy, &ldquo;was watching that <mark>arquebusier</mark> who had killed my brother.&rdquo; But one evening he resolved once and for all to be done with the trouble. I here gladly give him the word. <small> Michael Monahan, <a name="MMAL" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#MMAL"><cite title="source">Adventures in Life and Letters</cite></a> (1912) 309 [Cellini]</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: arquebusier: a soldier armed with an arquebus, an early type of portable gun.  <br>Raphael transcription: <a name="c05103h" href="c05all.htm#c05103h">VI.C.05:103(h)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
